ol.li:
	                We have
          m=\left\{
          \begin{array}{cc}
            \frac{10^t}{2^{t-s}} \amp \mbox{ if } t\geq s\\
            \frac{10^s}{5^{s-t}} \amp \mbox{ if } s\geq t\\
          \end{array}
            \right.
          so it follows that
          \frac{n}{m}=\left\{
          \begin{array}{cc}
            \frac{n\cdot 2^{t-s}}{10^{t}} \amp \mbox{ if } t\geq s\\
            \frac{n\cdot 5^{s-t}}{10^{s}} \amp \mbox{ if } s\geq t\\            
          \end{array}
            \right.
          which has a terminating decimal expansion.

            Write the decimal expansion as 
	      \amp d_{k}d_{k-1}d_{k-2}\cdots d_2d_1d_0.d_{-1}d_{-2}\cdots d_{-j}
	        \amp = \sum_{i=-j}^k d_i10^i
	        \amp = \sum_{i=-k}^j \frac{d_{-i}}{10^i}
	        \amp = \frac{\sum_{i=-k}^j d_{-i}
	      10^{j-i}}{10^{j}}

where the last equals sign is getting a common denominator. After
            reducing, the denominator has only 2 and 5 for prime
            factors. To finish, if you haven't done it already, use the
            Fundamental Theorem of Arithmetic to prove a little lemma to
            show that if a/b = n/m are both reduced fractions,
            with a,b,c,d are positive integers, then a=n
            and b=m.

statement.p:
Let S be a set. An algebra of
	    subsetsalgebra of sets

	   of S is a
      subset {\mathcal A}\subseteq {\mathcal P}(S) of the power set of
      S (see  above) for which the following properties hold.

\emptyset \in {\mathcal A}

For every X,Y\in {\mathcal A}, X\cap Y\in {\mathcal A}

For every X,Y\in {\mathcal A}, X\cup Y\in  {\mathcal A}

For every X\in {\mathcal  A}, S\setminus X \in {\mathcal A}


Show that the power set {\mathcal P}(S) is an algebra of
    sets for any set S.

Give an example of a collection of subsets of some set S for which
       exactly  three of the four set algebra properties hold.

ol.li:
We will use part a of the previous problem to show that the sets
on the left and right sides are equal by showing that their
characteristic functions are equal. Beginning with the characteristic
function for the set on the left side, we have

\chi_{A\cap(B\cup C)} \amp =
		  \chi_A \chi_{B\cup C} \amp \amp \text{(by part c above)}
\amp = \chi_A
(\chi_{B}\oplus \chi_{C} \oplus \chi_B\chi_C) \amp \amp
  \text{(by part d above)}
\amp = \chi_A\chi_B \oplus \chi_A\chi_C \oplus \chi_A\chi_B\chi_C
  \amp \amp \text{(distributing)}
\amp = \chi_A\chi_B \oplus \chi_A\chi_C \oplus (\chi_A)^2\chi_B\chi_C
  \amp \amp  \text{(by part b above)}
\amp = \chi_A\chi_B \oplus \chi_A\chi_C \oplus \chi_A\chi_B\chi_A\chi_C
  \amp \amp  \text{(rearranging)}
\amp = \chi_{A\cap B}\oplus \chi_{A\cap C} \oplus \chi_{A\cap B}\chi_{A\cap C}
  \amp \amp  \text{(by part c above)}
  \amp = \chi_{(A\cap B)\cup (A\cap C)} \amp \amp  \text{(by part d
  above)}.

The last expression is the characteristic function for the set on the
	      right side.

Here are the 5 partitions of S.

		\{a,b,c\}
		\{a,b\},\{c\}
		\{a,c\},\{b\}
		\{b,c\},\{a\}
		\{a\},\{b\},\{c\}

statement.p:
An equivalence relationequivalence relation on a set S is a set E\subseteq S\times S of ordered pairs of elements of S that satisfies the following.
(x,x)\in E for every x\in S (the reflexive property)
if (x,y) is in E then (y,x) is in E (the symmetric property)
if (x,y) is in E and (y,z) is in E, then (x,z) is in E (the transitive property)
Write out all possible equivalence relations for S=\{a,b,c\}.
Give an example of a set F\subseteq S\times S of ordered pairs of S=\{a,b,c\} that satisfies exactly two of the three properties in the definition of equivalence relation.

ol.li:
Here are the 5 equivalence relations on S.

		S\times S
		\{a,b\}\times \{a,b\}\cup \{(c,c)\}
		\{a,c\}\times \{a,c\}\cup\{(b,b)\}
		\{b,c\}\times \{b,c\}\cup\{(a,a)\}
		\{(a,a), (b,b), (c,c)\}
